All Implemented Interfaces:
PropertyValueSource, Map<String,​String>
public class PropertyMap extends VariableMap<String>
A property map is a VariableMap with strings as both keys and values.

Creating and Loading Property Maps

A property map can be created or loaded from a Resource with:

  • create() - Creates an empty property map
  • propertyMap(VariableMap) - Creates a property map from the given variable map
  • load(Listener, Resource) - Loads property map from the given resource
  • localized(Listener, PackagePath, Locale) - Loads a property map from the given package with a relative path from the given Locale of the form "locales/[language-name](/[country-name])?.

Conversions

  • copy() - A copy of this property map
  • BaseStringMap.asObject(Listener, Class) - Creates a new instance of the given class and populates its properties with the values in this property map using ObjectPopulator
  • BaseStringMap.asInt(String) - The given value as an int
  • BaseStringMap.asLong(String) - The given value as a long
  • BaseStringMap.asDouble(String) - The given value as a double
  • BaseStringMap.asCount(String) - The given value as a Count

Adding to Property Maps

In addition to the methods inherited from VariableMap, property maps add the following methods:

  • comment(String, String) - Attaches the given comment to the given key
  • add(Object, PropertyFilter) - Adds the properties of the given object that match the filter to this map

Saving Property Maps

  • save(WritableResource) - Saves this property map to the given resource
  • save(String, WritableResource) - Saves this property map to the given resource with the given heading

    • expanded

      public PropertyMap expanded()
      Overrides:
      expanded in class VariableMap<String>
      Returns:
      This variable map with all string values expanded by interpolating values for other keys in the map. For example, the entry for key "coordinate" might be the value "${location-x}, ${location-y}". If the value for the key "location-x" is "9" and the value for "location-y" is "81", then the expanded variable map will have the value "9, 81" for the key "coordinate"
